Great service. Speedy, attentive, friendly and courteous service from waiter/tress, bar and bus boy. However, this is not a “Cocina Boricua”(Puerto Rican kitchen) as advertised. Either the chef has changed to a Non-Puerto Rican Culinary specialist or the people who have written such rave reviews have no idea how Puerto Rican food should taste and appear. I will post a couple of images for reference. I ordered Asopao the Pollo (Puerto Rican Chicken Gumbo). The texture is supposed to be thick/creamy with a touch of chopped fresh long cilantro(recao) toward the end of cooking process. What I received was chicken broth with yellow rice placed in it and added chicken breast slithers. Watery no creamy texture. There seems to be a theme here with the chicken pieces! These ingredients were not cooked together to create the dish. Same issue with my sister in law’s arroz con pollo(chicken and Rice). The rice did not have chicken flavor. They combined plain yellow rice with chicken slithers/slices that seemed to be sautéed to reddish brown color. Cute presentation bringing the dishes out in small cazuelas but the food is BLAH! an offense to Puerto Rican culinary traditions.

Came in from out of town to visit with family and wanting to enjoy a nice ambiance along with some delicious Puerto Rican food and this place did not disappoint as we were welcomed and immediately seated and enjoyed some delicious and varied fruity versions of mojitos along with some appetizers while enjoying some enjoyable latin music playing in the background just at the right octave allowing conversations to flow without anyone screaming over each other. The main course was great for the most part although the tostones were a bit disappointing due to their being somewhat semi-sweet as they probably had started to mature. Nonetheless the staff was awesome even going out of their way to accommodate my sister's request for an avocado salad which they had depleted but went to the nearby grocer and purchased avocados just satisfy her request!😊 Later in the evening they began the karaoke night festivities which was a blast as me and my family decided that we'd be the background chorus for most of the night! It was a very nice crowd but not overcrowded and everyone just enjoying a great evening overall filled with lots of Puerto Rican love and laughter!😀

Amazing, authentic Puerto Rican couisine.  Large portions, well priced, and taste like Grandma’s Home cooking.  Although we ordered for pick up, the ambiance was modern yet warm and inviting.  The service was fast, feiendly and inviting; which is key in any hospitality service no matter the quality of food.  The order was correct and the pricing was just right.  I have already told a few family and friends about this hidden gem, and will be coming to visit and dine in very soon!  We need to support the mom and pop shops and the comfort and support of our communities that they bring.  The charm, authenticity and quality that bring a community together is what we need more of; not half fast, frozen generic chain restaurants.  We need to start supporting one another and bring back our values.  Chain restaurants are for airports and pit stops, not small neighborhoods.  No I do not know the owner, nor work for the owner of this restaurant, but something about a family owned business sparks my inner childhood and makes me sad to see that quality dicipating with our new, instant gratification, texting, head in the phone, technological generations.  So put the phones down, talk with people face to face, and enjoy the company of others.  Live in the moment, memories are much better in our feelings and thoughts than they are spent trying to get the right shot for Facebook.  Enjoy
